ARDUINO NANO:
Very compact → perfect for robots where space matters
Fits easily on  small chassis
Cheaper than many other boards
Good for student projects and prototypes
Works with the Arduino IDE
14 digital pins
8 analog pins
Can connect sensors + motor drivers (like TB6612FNG)








Arduino Nano works :
Reads inputs (sensors)
Processes logic (your code)
Controls outputs (motors, LEDs)

Input → Process → Output cycle:
Input:
Sensors send signals
(IR, ultrasonic, buttons)
Processing:
Arduino runs your program (written in C/C++)
Makes decisions
Output:
Sends signals to:
Motor driver (TB6612FNG)
LEDs
Buzzers

ARDUINO PIN CONFIGURATION:
1. Digital Pins (D0 – D13)
Total: 14 digital pins
Used for: ON/OFF signals
Special ones:
D0 (RX), D1 (TX) → Serial communication
D2, D3 → External interrupts
D3, D5, D6, D9, D10, D11 → PWM pins
2. PWM Pins (Speed control)
Used for motor speed control (important for TB6612FNG)
PWM Pins:
D3, D5, D6, D9, D10, D11
3. Analog Pins (A0 – A7)
Used to read analog signals (0–1023)
Example uses:
IR sensors
Potentiometers
A6, A7 → input only (no output)
4. Power Pins
5V → Power output to modules
3.3V → Low-power devices
GND → Ground
VIN → External power input (7–12V)
5. Communication Pins
UART (Serial):
D0 → RX
D1 → TX
I2C:
A4 → SDA
A5 → SCL
SPI:
D10 → SS
D11 → MOSI
D12 → MISO
D13 → SCK
6. Reset Pin
Restarts Arduino when triggered

